  "doc_id": "19420",
  "text": "A University of Cincinnati study [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] replicated a subset of the Liberty Mutual experiments to investigate the effects of an extended work shift (12 hours) on MAW and energy expenditure. Independent variables were lift frequency, height of lift (floor-toknuckle, knuckle-to-shoulder, and shoulder-to-reach), box size, and shift length. For a given condition of frequency, height, and box size, subjects selected MAWs first assuming an 8-hour shift and then assuming a 12-hour shift. Similar to the Liberty Mutual studies, the following results were significant (p Ͻ .05): (1) MAW decreased as lift frequency increased; (2) MAW decreased as box size increased; (3) MAW was greater at the floor-to-knuckle height than at the shoulder-to-reach height; and (4) MAW was greater for males than females.",
